summary:
Iran's Assembly of Experts appointed 56-year-old Mojtaba Khamenei, son of slain Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, as the new supreme leader. The decision occurred amid the US-Israeli war with Iran. Military leaders pledged allegiance to Mojtaba Khamenei. This follows the death of Ali Khamenei, who held the position since 1989. The appointment affects Iran's governance and its role in ongoing regional conflicts.

Brent crude oil prices reached $101.19 per barrel, up 9.2 percent, due to disruptions in Middle East production and shipping from the Iran war. Global consumers face higher gasoline prices. Bahrain's state oil company declared force majeure on shipments after an Iran attack, affecting Gulf exporters and buyers. G7 leaders plan talks on releasing emergency oil reserves, as prices rose 25 percent to 2022 highs. Israel struck Tehran oil depots and infrastructure to counter an imminent weapons threat, according to an Israeli spokesperson. The attacks impact Iranian civilians and leadership.

Thousands of displaced Palestinians crossed into northern Gaza after Israel permitted returns following a hostage release deal. Families reunited amid damaged buildings, though fighting continues. In eastern Lebanon, Hezbollah fighters clashed with Israeli ground forces landed by helicopter from Syria; Iran launched its first post-leadership drones at Israel. Lebanese civilians face intensified cross-border fighting, with ceasefire talks stalled. Rwanda-backed rebels overran Goma in the Democratic Republic of Congo, defeating troops and prompting gunfire and shelling; over one million residents were displaced. The UN warned of a humanitarian disaster as aid operations are endangered. NATO activated defenses after a deep-sea cable severance in the Baltic Sea, suspected as sabotage; European connectivity is at risk."}
